          "sequence": 56,
          "subtype": "message",
          "text": "Perfect! I've completed the fault localization analysis. Here's a summary of my findings:\n\n## Fault Localization Summary\n\n**Bug ID**: 207835 - ACPI Video Backlight Brightness Control Failure on Acer TravelMate 5735Z\n\n### Root Cause\nThe Acer TravelMate 5735Z is **missing from the `video_detect_dmi_table`** in `drivers/acpi/video_detect.c`. This causes the system to incorrectly default to the `acpi_backlight_vendor` type, which uses the acer_wmi driver for brightness control.\n\n### The Problem Flow\n1. At boot, `acpi_video_get_backlight_type()` in `video_detect.c` is called to determine which driver should handle backlight\n2. Since there's no DMI match for this device, the autodetection logic kicks in\n3. Without explicit ACPI_VIDEO_BACKLIGHT capability detection or other cues, it defaults to `acpi_backlight_vendor`\n4. The acer_wmi driver then registers its own backlight interface (which shows 5 levels)\n5. However, acer_wmi's brightness control doesn't actually work on this device\n\n### Why `acpi_backlight=native` Works\nWhen the user boots with `acpi_backlight=native`:\n- The kernel parameter overrides the default selection\n- The native intel_backlight driver is used instead\n- It properly supports 15-16 brightness levels and works correctly\n\n### The Fix\nAdd Acer TravelMate 5735Z to the `video_detect_dmi_table` with the `video_detect_force_native` callback. This will:\n- Make `acpi_video_get_backlight_type()` return `acpi_backlight_native` by default\n- Prevent acer_wmi from registering its broken brightness interface\n- Allow the native intel_backlight driver to handle brightness control\n\n**Files:** `drivers/acpi/video_detect.c`\n**Structure:** `video_detect_dmi_table` (needs a new entry for TravelMate 5735Z)\n**Confidence:** 95%",
